MENINGITIS - GHANA (02): FATAL, SUSPECTED PNEUMOCOCCAL, REQUEST FOR INFORMATION
****************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Fri 10 Nov 2017
Source: Ghana Web [edited]
https://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/health/Pneumococcal-Meningitis-killing-humans-Ghana-599363


Dreadful, life-threatening, and infectious pneumococcal meningitis has hit Ghana, taking 93 lives so far since last year [2016].

Pneumococcal meningitis is caused by _Streptococcus pneumoniae_, a bacterium that affects the lungs and is easily spread through coughing, sneezing, and prolonged body contact with an infected person. Living in a crowded setting, intimate kissing, and eating from the same bowl or drinking from the same cup as an infected person can equally help spread the disease-causing bacteria.

Babies and children, mostly under 18 months of age, in most cases stand a higher risk of acquiring the disease in the early stages of their lives.

The disease has an incubation period of about 2-10 days before producing symptoms, which include neck pain, neck stiffness, convulsion, and vomiting.

Seasonal reports on pneumococcal meningitis in Ghana usually come during the dry season from October to March, with the worst affected regions being the Ashanti, Central, Brong Ahafo and Northern region due to relatively low humidity and abundance of dust.

A thorough autopsy revealed that 4 students of Kumasi Academy Senior High in the Ashanti region died this year [2017] of the disease.

Marylin Amediwa, a nursing student at Pentecost University, when interviewed about the worrying disease, said that pneumococcal meningitis causes the same symptoms as malaria and fever, sounding a word of caution to Ghanaians to refrain from self-medication. [Although both meningitis and malaria present with malaise, shaking chills, and fever, meningitis, unlike malaria, presents additionally with neck stiffness and pain].

An infected person stands a chance of receiving early treatment with prescribed antibiotics should the victim consult the hospital on time when symptom show themselves.

[Byline: Esther Agyei Ayimwa]

