Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Maps of Ghana can be seen at http://www.ezilon.com/maps/images/africa/political-map-of-Ghana.gif and https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=5439630,50377.

ProMED-mail last posted on a pneumococcal meningitis outbreak in Ghana in January 2016, when the number of cases had risen to 55 and the number of deaths to "slightly over 19."

Use of a pneumococcal conjugate vaccine would be beneficial. Pneumococcal conjugate vaccines reduce nasopharyngeal carriage of serotypes of _Streptococcus pneumoniae_ contained in the vaccine and thus person-to-person transmission of these pathogens, which occurs by close contact with respiratory secretions or saliva.

In neighboring Burkina Faso, a study found that the 7-valent pneumococcal conjugate vaccine, which includes serotypes 4, 6B, 9V, 14, 18C, 19F, and 23F, was protective against only 8 per cent of the local isolates (http://cid.oxfordjournals.org/content/43/6/693.full). The 13-valent pneumococcal conjugate vaccine, Prevnar 13, which covers serotypes 1, 3, 4, 5, 6A, 6B, 7F, 9V, 14, 18C, 19A, 19F, and 23F, may be more effective, but we are not told the serotypes of pneumococci causing this outbreak in Ghana.

The 13-valent pneumococcal conjugate vaccine is included in the recommended routine infant immunization schedule in the U.S. (https://www.cdc.gov/vaccines/schedules/hcp/imz/child-adolescent.html), but not in Ghana (http://collections.infocollections.org/whocountry/en/d/Js6861e/6.1.html#Js6861e.6.1).

Information from knowledgeable sources regarding the serotypes of _S. pneumoniae_ involved in this outbreak in Ghana would be welcomed. - Mod.ML

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=5439630,53.]
